===========================================================================================================

class Solution{

   public boolean isSubsequence(String s, String t){
      int len1=s.length();
      int len2=t.length();

      int i=0;
      int j=0;

      while(i<len1 && j<len2){
        if(s.charAt(i)==t.charAt(j)){
         i++;
        }
        j++;
      }
      return i==len1;
   }
}


============================

You have two strings:

s â†’ a small word (what you want to find)

t â†’ a big word (where you search)

Your task is to check:

â€œCan I find all letters of the small word in order inside the big word?â€

âš ï¸ Important:

Letters must be in the same order

They do NOT have to be next to each other

Example
s = "abc"
t = "a h b g d c"


You can pick:

a â†’ âœ”

then b â†’ âœ”

then c â†’ âœ”

So "abc" is a subsequence of t.

ðŸ§  How the Code Thinks (Very Simple)

Think of:

One finger on string s

One finger on string t

We move the fingers step by step.

ðŸ§© The Code
class Solution {

   public boolean isSubsequence(String s, String t) {


ðŸ‘‰ This function will return:

true â†’ YES, it is a subsequence

false â†’ NO, it is not

ðŸ“ Step 1: Measure the strings
int len1 = s.length();
int len2 = t.length();


We check:

How long is the small word?

How long is the big word?

ðŸ‘‰ Step 2: Put fingers at the start
int i = 0;
int j = 0;


i â†’ finger on small word (s)

j â†’ finger on big word (t)

Both fingers start at position 0 (the first letter).

ðŸ” Step 3: Start walking
while (i < len1 && j < len2) {


This means:

â€œKeep walking as long as:

we still have letters left in s

AND letters left in tâ€

ðŸ‘€ Step 4: Compare letters
if (s.charAt(i) == t.charAt(j)) {
    i++;
}


This says:

â€œIf the current letter of s and t are the same,
then move the finger on s forward.â€

Why?

Because we found the letter we were looking for

ðŸš¶ Step 5: Always move in t
j++;


This means:

â€œWhether letters match or not,
always move forward in the big word.â€

Why?

Because you are searching inside t

ðŸ Step 6: Final check
return i == len1;


This means:

â€œDid we find all letters of the small word?â€

If i reached the end â†’ âœ” YES

Otherwise â†’ âŒ NO

ðŸ§ª Simple Example Walkthrough
Input
s = "ab"
t = "axb"

Step-by-step
s[i]	t[j]	Match?	Action
a	a	âœ”	i++, j++
b	x	âŒ	j++
b	b	âœ”	i++, j++

Now:

i == len1 â†’ âœ”

Return true.

ðŸŽ¯ One-line explanation (child-friendly)

â€œWe walk through the big word and try to find each letter of the small word in order.â€
